Your Summary

You were diagnosed with breast cancer in March 2021. After your diagnosis, you had chemotherapy treatment which worked well at shrinking the cancer, followed by an operation to remove it. You then had radiotherapy and have been taking a hormone tablet since then. Unfortunately, in 2023 scans showed the cancer had come back and spread to your liver and bones. You're currently receiving ongoing treatment to control this, and your care team is closely monitoring your progress to ensure you receive the best possible care.

Your Diagnosis

Metastatic Breast Cancer (Stage IV)

Your diagnosis was confirmed on 15 March 2021.

Your specific type of breast cancer:

Oestrogen receptor positive (ER+)
Your cancer cells have receptors that respond to the hormone oestrogen. This means hormone therapy medicines can be used to help treat your cancer.
Progesterone receptor positive (PR+)
Your cancer cells also respond to the hormone progesterone.
HER2 negative
Your cancer cells have normal levels of the HER2 protein.

Learn more about breast cancer

For trusted information about your diagnosis and what to expect, visit Cancer Research UK - Breast Cancer . You can also read about stages and grades to better understand your results.

Your Treatment

You are currently receiving treatment for your breast cancer. Your care team reviews your treatment regularly to make sure it's working well for you.

Current Treatment
Ribociclib + Fulvestrant
Started 04 November 2024

Ribociclib is a targeted therapy tablet (CDK4/6 inhibitor), and fulvestrant is a hormone therapy injection.

You have received 5 different treatments since your diagnosis. See the Treatments tab for full details.
